Currently a throttled function will be invoked with the last arguments provided. I'm looking for a way to batch all the arguments provided (while the function is being throttled), and then invoking the function with those batched arguments. Normally the arguments are objects and `_.assign` is used to batch them.

Example:

``` javascript
var func = _.throttle(
  function update(values) { ... },
  100,
  {batched: true}
);

func({a: 'foo', b: 'hello'});
func({a: 'bar'});
func({c: 'world'});

// `update` is invoked with ({a: 'bar', b: 'hello', c: 'world'})
```

So, this is precisely the sort of iteration-related, actually-relatively-simple task that I usually rely on Lodash to implement for me; so, in that vein, would the following function, or an approximation thereof, be welcome?

```
function isShallowEqual(v, o) {
    for(var key in v)
        if(!(key in o) || v[key] !== o[key])
            return false

    for(var key in o)
        if(!(key in v) || v[key] !== o[key])
            return false

    return true }
```

