For example:

``` js
var myObj = {
  a: 1,
  b: 2,
  get length () {
    console.log('getter for `length` was activated');
    return 3;
  }
}

console.log(_.keys(myObj))

/* Output:
getter for `length` was activated
getter for `length` was activated
getter for `length` was activated
[ 'a', 'b', 'length' ]
*/
```

The issue comes from the fact that `_.keys` internally calls `_.isArrayLike`, which checks for the `length` property. Since several other functions also call `_.keys` internally (such as `_.omit`, `_.pickBy`, etc.), these functions activate the getter as well.

In a similar vein, this also occurs with ES6 Proxies:

``` js
var myProxy = new Proxy({}, {get: function (target, key) {
  console.log('getting property for key ' + String(key));
  // do a possibly-time-consuming operation
  return target[key];
}})
```

(The Proxy issue could be solved by adding a `'length' in value` check in `_.isArrayLike`, although this would have a slight performance impact.)

Admittedly, Lodash makes no guarantees about which properties it will/won't access, and this is a fairly uncommon use-case. However, it seems like accessing the `length` property is unnecessary in this case since `Object.keys` could be used instead.

When transforming data structures and adding to nested arrays (or creating an array on the fly), we frequently see the following pattern:

``` javascript
if (_.has(o, 'arr')) {
  o.arr.push(val);
} else {
  _.set(o, 'arr', [val]);
}
```

It would be convenient to replace this with a nice, readable single line.  A lodash push method could follow the same signature as _.has, _.get, _.set, and friends:

``` javascript
_.push(o, 'arr', val);
```

For example, when looping through a data set...

``` javascript
if (_.has(myCalendar.eventsLookup, [userid, dateKey, 'calendarEntries'])) {
  _.get(myCalendar.eventsLookup, [userid, dateKey, 'calendarEntries']).push(calendarEntry);
} else {
  _.set(myCalendar.eventsLookup, [userid, dateKey, 'calendarEntries'], [calendarEntry]);
}
```

could be simplified to a single line...

``` javascript
_.push(myCalendar.eventsLookup, [userid, dateKey, 'calendarEntries'], calendarEntry);
```

